@craffel @faroit @carlthome How does the following sound as a smart docstring comment?
Please be aware that this function does not compute permutations on the possible relations between reference_sources and estimated_sources due to the dangers of a changing permutation. Therefore (by default), it assumes that reference_sources[i] corresponds to estimated_sources[i]. To enable computing permutations please set compute_permutation to be True and check that the returned perm is identical for all windows.

Actually, `table` defined as `u32`:

http://lxr.free-electrons.com/source/include/net/fib_rules.h#L18

but in `fib_rule_hdr` it is indeed `u8`:

http://lxr.free-electrons.com/source/include/uapi/linux/fib_rules.h#L24 while `flags` is `u32` as expected.

but as you can see there are two bytes resrerved in the structure and they were there since the first commit:
https://github.com/torvalds/linux/commit/14c0b97ddfc2944982d078b8e33b088840068976

```c
 18 struct fib_rule_hdr {
 19         __u8            family;
 20         __u8            dst_len;
 21         __u8            src_len;
 22         __u8            tos;
 23 
 24         __u8            table;
 25         __u8            res1;   /* reserved */
 26         __u8            res2;   /* reserved */
 27         __u8            action;
 28 
 29         __u32           flags;
 30 };
```

so maybe they actually do get filled? or, if not, did somebody forget to patch the kernel?

also, I have noticed that in kernel tree there are direct copy operations like

```c
frh->table = rule->table;
```

see http://lxr.free-electrons.com/source/net/core/fib_rules.c?v=3.7#L548

while in del rule in the same file they do a 

```c
if (frh->table && (frh_get_table(frh, tb) != rule->table))
```

so I can assume that this inconsistency is definitely a kernel bug and should be filed to the tracker

