Certainly. There is no syntax for specifying cmap table values, but it makes sense to support such in any case. I would define such values as being the final pass of cmap definition. The current sourcesfor encoding info  would work as they do currently, but any values defined in the feature file would override any values defined elsewhere.

  table cmap {
     subtable <name> {
     	platform <int>;
     	language <int>;
     	script <int>;
     	format  <int>;
     	<encoding value> <glyphName>;
     	...
     } <name>;
  } head;

The 'format' keyword is optional, and is intended only to allow overriding the heuristics for selecting a format.

Encoding value may be either decimal or hex.
Hex values will be preceede by 0x.
If any encoding value in the subtable is requires more than two bytes, all values will be promoted to 4 byte value. 

The code point record may be two or three white space delimited fields. The last field is the glyph name. Preceding fields make up the encoding value. If the encoding value contains two fields, it is assumed to be a Unicode variation selector.

